===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|book|lang=enm|sc=Latn}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|bōc||a book, a document, register, catalog, a legal document, a bill of divorce, a charter, a title deed, conveyance, a volume, literary work, pages, main division of a work}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*bōks||beech, book}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*bheh₁g̑ós||beech}}, {{term/t|ine-pro|*bʰeh₂ǵos}}.
{{rel-top|cognates}}Cognate with {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|buik|lang=sco}}, {{term|beuk||book|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|boek||book|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|Book|lang=nds}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|boek||book|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Buch||book|lang=de}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|bog|lang=da}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|bok||book|lang=sv}}. Related also to Latin {{term/t|la|fāgus||beech}}, Russian {{term|бук|tr=buk|lang=ru||beech}}, Albanian {{term|bung|lang=sq||chestnut, oak}}, Ancient Greek {{term|φηγός|tr=phēgós|lang=grc||oak}}, Armenian {{term|բուն|tr=bun||trunk|lang=hy}}, Kurdish {{term|bûz||elm}}. More at [[beech]], [[buckwheat]].
{{rel-bottom}}
The sense development of ''beech'' to ''book'' is explained by the fact that smooth gray beech bark was commonly used as [[bookfell]].<ref>J.P. Mallory, ''Encyclopedia of Indo-European Culture'', s.v. "beech" (London: Fitroy-Dearborn, 1997), 58.</ref>

